The paper deals with distributed consensus protocols and their security properties, which are typically studied in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses attacks on the protocol, which falls under the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. The paper proposes a new protocol for distributed consensus, which involves the use of proof-of-work quorums, a concept that is related to distributed systems (cs.DS) and system and control theory (cs.SY). Finally, the paper evaluates the proposed protocol using simulations, which is a common technique in the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
